## Planning pass summary — sprint `apra-fleet-eft`

This was a **re-planning pass**: the features+tasks DAG from a prior pass already existed and is structurally sound. I validated it against the graph-semantics contract and closed the only gaps found — I did **not** re-plan or add scope.

### DAG state (scoped to `apra-fleet-eft`)
- **9 in-scope P1/P2 features** (eft.1–eft.9), each correctly parented under the epic (grouping only), each with ≥1 `[impl]` task and exactly one `[test]` task.
- **Test tasks** are wired `blocks`-downstream of their sibling impl tasks; cross-feature ordering deps (e.g. `5.2` ← `4.4`, `9.4` ← `ire`) are all sibling-level, never parent↔child.
- `apra-fleet-ire` (portable-dolt installer) is referenced as a child/prereq of the Phase-2 dolt feature — left in place, not re-created.
- **Acyclicity: verified.** `bd list --parent apra-fleet-eft --ready --json` returns 23 ready issues (non-empty → no deadlock); all 9 features appear in the ready set (none blocked by their own children); `bd dep cycles` → clean.

### Gaps fixed
Two in-scope **P1 bug leaves** were missing the required model-tier metadata:
- `apra-fleet-eft.13` (EADDRINUSE fixed-port cascade) → `{"model":"standard"}`
- `apra-fleet-eft.6.7` (dashboard misclassifies grandchild tasks as Backlog) → `{"model":"standard"}`

Both already carried thorough acceptance criteria (root cause + fix direction + required regression coverage), so only the metadata was added. All ~50 leaf tasks now carry a valid tier (`cheap`/`standard`/`premium`) in `metadata.model` — the sole recorded location.

### Deliberately left alone (out of scope)
- `apra-fleet-eft.10/11/12` are **P3 Phase-3** features (server-side reservation, vendored contract updates, deferred crash-resume/merger-agent). This sprint's goal priority is **P1/P2**, and the epic plan records these as the longer tail / explicitly deferred. I did not decompose them or add tiers — doing so would add scope beyond the stated sprint priority.

No PLAN.md / progress.json written; no issues closed. The beads DAG is the deliverable and is ready for `plan-reviewer`.
